# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nanoparticle-drug-delivery
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The first dendrimers were made by divergent synthesis approaches by Fritz Vögtle in 1978, R.G.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Denkewalter at Allied Corporation in 1981, Donald Tomalia at Dow Chemical in 1983 and in 1985, and by George R.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] In 1990 a convergent synthetic approach was introduced by Craig Hawker and Jean Fréchet.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimer popularity then greatly increased, resulting in more than 5,000 scientific papers and patents by the year 2005.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The name comes from two Greek words: "dendron" meaning 'tree' and "meros" meaning 'part'.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendritic molecules are characterized by structural perfection.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers and dendrons are monodisperse and usually highly symmetric, spherical compounds.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The field of dendritic molecules can be roughly divided into low-molecular weight and high-molecular weight species.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The first category includes dendrimers and dendrons, and the latter includes dendronized polymers, hyperbranched polymers, and the polymer brush.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] A hyperbranched polymer is similar to a dendrimer, but more randomly structured.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] A hyperbranched polymer has a number of randomly distributed *linear constitutional repeating units*.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The properties of dendrimers are dominated by the functional groups on the molecular surface.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers may have a single surface functional group, or may be modified to allow for multiple functional groups on the surface.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] But some dendrimers have functional groups inside, not on the surface.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendritic encapsulation of functional molecules allows for the isolation of the active site, a structure that mimics that of active sites in biomaterials.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Also, it is possible to make dendrimers water-soluble, unlike most polymers, by functionalizing their outer shell with charged species or other hydrophilic groups.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Other controllable properties of dendrimers include toxicity, crystallinity, tecto-dendrimer formation, and chirality.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] In a dendrimer, the monomers are arranged in generations.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The monomers in the "core" are generation 0, written as G0.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The monomers attached to G0 are generation 1, written as G1, etc.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] A dendrimer is called a "first-generation dendrimer" if it has monomers of G0 and G1, but not G2.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Similarly for "second-generation dendrimer" and so on.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] In general, an n-th generation dendrimer is synthesized by *n* repeated branching cycles.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] For example, if a dendrimer is made by convergent synthesis, and the branching reactions are performed onto the core molecule three times, the resulting dendrimer is a third-generation dendrimer.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Each successive generation results in a dendrimer roughly twice the molecular weight of the previous generation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Higher generation dendrimers also have more exposed functional groups on the surface, which can later be used to customize the dendrimer for a given application.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] A dendrimer has three major components: a core, an inner shell, and an outer shell.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Ideally, an experimenter can design a synthesis process, to obtain a dendrimer with different designated functionalities in each of these portions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] This allows the experimenter to finely control properties of the final dendrimer, such as solubility, thermal stability, and attachment of compounds for particular applications.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The experimenter can also design the synthesis processes to precisely control the size and number of branches on the dendrimer.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] There are two defined methods of dendrimer synthesis, divergent synthesis and convergent synthesis.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] However, because the actual reactions consist of many steps needed to protect the active site, it is difficult to synthesize dendrimers using either method.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] This makes dendrimers hard to make and very expensive to purchase.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The dendrimer is assembled from a multifunctional core, which is extended outward by a series of reactions, commonly a Michael reaction.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Each step of the reaction must be driven to full completion to prevent mistakes in the dendrimer, which can cause trailing generations (some branches are shorter than the others).
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Such impurities can impact the functionality and symmetry of the dendrimer, but are extremely difficult to purify out because the relative size difference between perfect and imperfect dendrimers is very small.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers are built from small molecules that end up at the surface of the sphere, and reactions proceed inward building inward and are eventually attached to a core.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] This method makes it much easier to remove impurities and shorter branches along the way, so that the final dendrimer is more monodisperse.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] However dendrimers made this way are not as large as those made by divergent methods because crowding due to steric effects along the core is limiting.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers have been prepared via click chemistry, employing Diels-Alder reactions, thiol-ene and thiol-yne reactions and azide-alkyne reactions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] There are ample avenues that can be opened by exploring this chemistry in dendrimer synthesis.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] One of the first dendrimers, the Newkome dendrimer, was synthesized in 1985.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] This macromolecule is also commonly known by the name arborol.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The figure outlines the mechanism of the first two generations of arborol through a divergent route (discussed below).
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The synthesis is started by nucleophilic substitution of 1-bromopentane by *triethyl sodiomethanetricarboxylate* in dimethylformamide and benzene.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The ester groups were then reduced by lithium aluminium hydride to a triol in a deprotection step.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Activation of the chain ends was achieved by converting the alcohol groups to tosylate groups with tosyl chloride and pyridine.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The tosyl group then served as leaving groups in another reaction with the tricarboxylate, forming generation two.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Further repetition of the two steps leads to higher generations of arborol.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Poly(amidoamine), or PAMAM, is perhaps the most well known dendrimer.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The core of PAMAM is a diamine (commonly ethylenediamine), which is reacted with methyl acrylate, and then another ethylenediamine to make the generation-0 (G-0) PAMAM.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Successive reactions create higher generations, which tend to have different properties.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Lower generations can be thought of as flexible molecules with no appreciable inner regions, while medium-sized (G-3 or G-4) do have internal space that is essentially separated from the outer shell of the dendrimer.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Very large (G-7 and greater) dendrimers can be thought of more like solid particles with very dense surfaces due to the structure of their outer shell.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The functional group on the surface of PAMAM dendrimers is ideal for click chemistry, which gives rise to many potential applications.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimer synthesis is still difficult and expensive.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] At this time, there are only a few companies that sell dendrimers; Polymer Factory Sweden AB commercializes biocompatible bis-MPA dendrimers and Dendritech is the only kilogram-scale producers of PAMAM dendrimers.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] NanoSynthons, LLC from Mount Pleasant, Michigan, USA produces PAMAM dendrimers and other proprietary dendrimers.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Applications of dendrimers typically involve conjugating other chemical species to the dendrimer surface that can function as detecting agents (such as a dye molecule), affinity ligands, targeting components, radioligands, imaging agents, or pharmaceutically active compounds.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers have very strong potential for these applications because their structure can lead to multivalent systems.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] In other words, one dendrimer molecule has hundreds of possible sites to couple to an active species.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Researchers aimed to utilize the hydrophobic environments of the dendritic media to conduct photochemical reactions that generate the products that are synthetically challenged.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Carboxylic acid and phenol-terminated water-soluble dendrimers were synthesized to establish their utility in drug delivery as well as conducting chemical reactions in their interiors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] This might allow researchers to attach both targeting molecules and drug molecules to the same dendrimer, which could reduce negative side effects of medications on healthy cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers can also be used as a solubilizing agent.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Since their introduction in the mid-1980s, this novel class of dendrimer architecture has been a prime candidate for host–guest chemistry.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers with hydrophobic core and hydrophilic periphery have shown to exhibit micelle-like behavior and have container properties in solution.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The use of dendrimers as unimolecular micelles was proposed by Newkome in 1985.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] This analogy highlighted the utility of dendrimers as solubilizing agents.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The majority of drugs available in pharmaceutical industry are hydrophobic in nature and this property in particular creates major formulation problems.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] This drawback of drugs can be ameliorated by dendrimeric scaffolding, which can be used to encapsulate as well as to solubilize the drugs because of the capability of such scaffolds to participate in extensive hydrogen bonding with water.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimer labs are trying to manipulate dendrimer's solubilizing trait, to explore dendrimers for drug delivery and to target specific carriers.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] For dendrimers to be able to be used in pharmaceutical applications, they must surmount the required regulatory hurdles to reach market.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] One dendrimer scaffold designed to achieve this is the polyethoxyethylglycinamide (PEE-G) dendrimer.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] This dendrimer scaffold has been designed and shown to have high HPLC purity, stability, aqueous solubility and low inherent toxicity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Approaches for delivering unaltered natural products using polymeric carriers is of widespread interest.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers have been explored for the encapsulation of hydrophobic compounds and for the delivery of anticancer drugs.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The physical characteristics of dendrimers, including their monodispersity, water solubility, encapsulation ability, and large number of functionalizable peripheral groups make these macromolecules appropriate candidates for drug delivery vehicles.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers are particularly versatile drug delivery devices due to the wide range of chemical modifications that can be made to increase in vivo suitability and allow for site-specific targeted drug delivery.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] In the case of a dendrimer prodrug structure, linking of a drug to a dendrimer may be direct or linker-mediated depending on desired release kinetics.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Such a linker may be pH-sensitive, enzyme catalyzed, or a disulfide bridge.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The wide range of terminal functional groups available for dendrimers allows for many different types of linker chemistries, providing yet another tunable component on the system.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Polyethylene glycol (PEG) is a common modification for dendrimers to modify their surface charge and circulation time.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Surface charge can influence the interactions of dendrimers with biological systems, such as amine-terminal modified dendrimers which have a propensity to interact with cell membranes with anionic charge.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Certain in vivo studies have shown polycationic dendrimers to be cytotoxic through membrane permeabilization, a phenomenon that could be partially mitigated via addition of PEGylation caps on amine groups, resulting in lower cytotoxicity and lower red blood cell hemolysis.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Additionally, studies have found that PEGylation of dendrimers results in higher drug loading, slower drug release, longer circulation times in vivo, and lower toxicity in comparison to counterparts without PEG modifications.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Numerous targeting moieties have been used to modify dendrimer biodistribution and allow for targeting to specific organs.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] For example, folate receptors are overexpressed in tumor cells and are therefore promising targets for localized drug delivery of chemotherapeutics.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Folic acid conjugation to PAMAM dendrimers has been shown to increase targeting and decrease off-target toxicity while maintaining on-target cytotoxicity of chemotherapeutics such as methotrexate, in mouse models of cancer.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Antibody-mediated targeting of dendrimers to cell targets has also shown promise for targeted drug delivery.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] As epidermal growth factor receptors (EGFRs) are often overexpressed in brain tumors, EGFRs are a convenient target for site-specific drug delivery.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The delivery of boron to cancerous cells is important for effective neutron capture therapy, a cancer treatment which requires a large concentration of boron in cancerous cells and a low concentration in healthy cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] A boronated dendrimer conjugated with a monoclonal antibody drug that targets EGFRs was used in rats to successfully deliver boron to cancerous cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Modifying nanoparticle dendrimers with peptides has also been successful for targeted destruction of colorectal (HCT-116) cancer cells in a co-culture scenario.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Targeting peptides can be used to achieve site- or cell-specific delivery, and it has been shown that these peptides increase in targeting specificity when paired with dendrimers.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Specifically, gemcitabine-loaded YIGSR-CMCht/PAMAM, a unique kind of dendrimer nanoparticle, induces a targeted mortality on these cancer cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] This is performed via selective interaction of the dendrimer with laminin receptors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Peptide dendrimers may be employed in the future to precisely target cancer cells and deliver chemotherapeutic agents.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The cellular uptake mechanism of dendrimers can also be tuned using chemical targeting modifications.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Non-modified PAMAM-G4 dendrimer is taken up into activated microglia by fluid phase endocytosis.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Conversely, mannose modification of hydroxyl PAMAM-G4 dendrimers was able to change the mechanism of internalization to mannose-receptor (CD206) mediated endocytosis.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Additionally, mannose modification was able to change the biodistribution in the rest of the body in rabbits.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers have the potential to completely change the pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic (PK/PD) profiles of a drug.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] As carriers, the PK/PD is no longer determined by the drug itself but by the dendrimer's localization, drug release, and dendrimer excretion.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] ADME properties are very highly tunable by varying dendrimer size, structure, and surface characteristics.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] While G9 dendrimers accumulate very heavily to the liver and spleen, G6 dendrimers tend to accumulate more broadly.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] As molecular weight increases, urinary clearance and plasma clearance decrease while terminal half-life increases.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] To increase patient compliance with prescribed treatment, delivery of drugs orally is often preferred to other routes of drug administration.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] However oral bioavailability of many drugs tends to be very low.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers can be used to increase the solubility and stability of orally-administered drugs and increase drug penetration through the intestinal membrane.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The bioavailability of PAMAM dendrimers conjugated to a chemotherapeutic has been studied in mice; it was found that around 9% of dendrimer administered orally was found intact in circulation and that minimal dendrimer degradation occurred in the gut.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Intravenous dendrimer delivery shows promise as gene vectors to deliver genes to various organs in the body, and even tumors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] One study found that through intravenous injection, a combination of PPI dendrimers and gene complexes resulted in gene expression in the liver, and another study showed that a similar injection regressed the growth of tumors in observed animals.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The primary obstacle to transdermal drug delivery is the epidermis.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Hydrophobic drugs have a very difficult time penetrating the skin layer, as they partition heavily into skin oils.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Recently, PAMAM dendrimers have been used as delivery vehicles for NSAIDS to increase hydrophilicity, allowing greater drug penetration.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] These modifications act as polymeric transdermal enhancers allowing drugs to more easily penetrate the skin barrier.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers may also act as new ophthalmic vehicles for drug delivery, which are different from the polymers currently used for this purpose.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] A study by Vanndamme and Bobeck used PAMAM dendrimers as ophthalmic delivery vehicles in rabbits for two model drugs and measured the ocular residence time of this delivery to be comparable and in some cases greater than current bioadhesive polymers used in ocular delivery.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] This result indicates that administered drugs were more active and had increased bioavailability when delivered via dendrimers than their free-drug counterparts.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Additionally, photo-curable, drug-eluting dendrimer-hyaluronic acid hydrogels have been used as corneal sutures applied directly to the eye.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] These hydrogel sutures have shown efficacy as a medical device in rabbit models that surpasses traditional sutures and minimizes corneal scarring.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimer drug delivery has also shown major promise as a potential solution for many traditionally difficult drug delivery problems.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] In the case of drug delivery to the brain, dendrimers are able to take advantage of the EPR effect and blood-brain barrier (BBB) impairment to cross the BBB effectively in vivo.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] For example, hydroxyl-terminated PAMAM dendrimers possess an intrinsic targeting ability to inflamed macrophages in the brain, verified using fluorescently labeled neutral generation dendrimers in a rabbit model of cerebral palsy.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] This intrinsic targeting has enabled drug delivery in a variety of conditions, ranging from cerebral palsy and other neuroinflammatory disorders to traumatic brain injury and hypothermic circulatory arrest, across a variety of animal models ranging from mice and rabbits to canines.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimer uptake into the brain correlates with severity of inflammation and BBB impairment and it is believed that the BBB impairment is the key driving factor allowing dendrimer penetration.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Localization is heavily skewed towards activated microglia.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimer-conjugated N-acetyl cysteine has shown efficacy in vivo as an anti-inflammatory at more than 1000-fold lower dose than free drug on a drug basis, reversing the phenotype of cerebral palsy, Rett syndrome, macular degeneration and other inflammatory diseases.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Starpharma, an Australian pharmaceutical company, has multiple products that have either already been approved for use or are in the clinical trial phase.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] SPL7013, also known as astodrimer sodium, is a hyperbranched polymer used in Starpharma's VivaGel line of pharmaceuticals that is currently approved to treat bacterial vaginosis and prevent the spread of HIV, HPV, and HSV in Europe, Southeast Asia, Japan, Canada, and Australia.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Due to SPL7013's broad antiviral action, it has recently been tested by the company as a potential drug to treat SARS-CoV-2.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The company states preliminary in-vitro studies show high efficacy in preventing SARS-CoV-2 infection in cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The ability to deliver pieces of DNA to the required parts of a cell includes many challenges.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Current research is being performed to find ways to use dendrimers to traffic genes into cells without damaging or deactivating the DNA.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] To maintain the activity of DNA during dehydration, the dendrimer/DNA complexes were encapsulated in a water-soluble polymer, and then deposited on or sandwiched in functional polymer films with a fast degradation rate to mediate gene transfection.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Based on this method, PAMAM dendrimer/DNA complexes were used to encapsulate functional biodegradable polymer films for substrate mediated gene delivery.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Research has shown that the fast-degrading functional polymer has great potential for localized transfection.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers have potential applications in sensors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Studied systems include proton or pH sensors using poly(propylene imine), cadmium-sulfide/polypropylenimine tetrahexacontaamine dendrimer composites to detect fluorescence signal quenching, and poly(propylenamine) first and second generation dendrimers for metal cation photodetection amongst others.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Research in this field is vast and ongoing due to the potential for multiple detection and binding sites in dendritic structures.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers also are used in the synthesis of monodisperse metallic nanoparticles.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Poly(amidoamine), or PAMAM, dendrimers are utilized for their tertiary amine groups at the branching points within the dendrimer.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Metal ions are introduced to an aqueous dendrimer solution and the metal ions form a complex with the lone pair of electrons present at the tertiary amines.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] After complexation, the ions are reduced to their zerovalent states to form a nanoparticle that is encapsulated within the dendrimer.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] These nanoparticles range in width from 1.5 to 10 nanometers and are called dendrimer-encapsulated nanoparticles.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Given the widespread use of pesticides, herbicides and insecticides in modern farming, dendrimers are also being used by companies to help improve the delivery of agrochemicals to enable healthier plant growth and to help fight plant diseases.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers are also being investigated for use as blood substitutes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Their steric bulk surrounding a heme-mimetic centre significantly slows degradation compared to free heme, and prevents the cytotoxicity exhibited by free heme.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendritic functional polymer polyamidoamine (PAMAM) is used to prepare core shell structure i.e. microcapsules and utilized in formulation of self-healing coatings of conventional and renewable origins.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Different generations of polyamidoamine dendrimers have recently been implemented as selective contacts in photovoltaic devices.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Dendrimers in drug-delivery systems is an example of various host–guest interactions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The interaction between host and guest, the dendrimer and the drug, respectively, can either be hydrophobic or covalent.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Hydrophobic interaction between host and guest is considered "encapsulated," while covalent interactions are considered to be conjugated.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The use of dendrimers in medicine has shown to improve drug delivery by increasing the solubility and bioavailability of the drug.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] In conjunction, dendrimers can increase both cellular uptake and targeting ability, and decrease drug resistance.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] The solubility of various nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAID) increases when they are encapsulated in PAMAM dendrimers.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] This study shows the enhancement of NSAID solubility is due to the electrostatic interactions between the surface amine groups in PAMAM and the carboxyl groups found in NSAIDs.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Contributing to the increase in solubility are the hydrophobic interactions between the aromatic groups in the drugs and the interior cavities of the dendrimer.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] When a drug is encapsulated within a dendrimer, its physical and physiological properties remains unaltered, including non-specificity and toxicity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] However, when the dendrimer and the drug are covalently linked together, it can be used for specific tissue targeting and controlled release rates.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Covalent conjugation of multiple drugs on dendrimer surfaces can pose a problem of insolubility.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] This principle is also being studied for cancer treatment application.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Several groups have encapsulated anti-cancer medications such as: Camptothecin, Methotrexate, and Doxorubicin.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Results from these research has shown that dendrimers have increased aqueous solubility, slowed release rate, and possibly control cytotoxicity of the drugs.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Cisplatin has been conjugated to PAMAM dendrimers that resulted in the same pharmacological results as listed above, but the conjugation also helped in accumulating cisplatin in solid tumors in intravenous administration.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] In 2006, a detailed investigation on the toxicological profile of fifth generation poly propyleneimine dendrimers was published.[91] They investigated four forms of functionalized dendrimers including Lysine, Phenyalalanine, Mannose and Lactose.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] These dendrimeric systems were investigated for haemolytic toxicity, cytotoxicity, hematological profile and immunogenicity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/dendrimer] Their study revealed that the functionalized forms of dendrimers were less toxic and have greater potential as drug delivery vehicle.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] The **enhanced permeability and retention** (**EPR**) **effect** is a controversial concept by which molecules of certain sizes (typically liposomes, nanoparticles, and macromolecular drugs) tend to accumulate in tumor tissue much more than they do in normal tissues.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] The general explanation that is given for this phenomenon is that, in order for tumor cells to grow quickly, they must stimulate the production of blood vessels.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] VEGF and other growth factors are involved in cancer angiogenesis.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] Tumor cell aggregates as small as 150–200 μm, start to become dependent on blood supply carried out by neovasculature for their nutritional and oxygen supply.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] These newly formed tumor vessels are usually abnormal in form and architecture.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] They are poorly aligned defective endothelial cells with wide fenestrations, lacking a smooth muscle layer, or innervation with a wider lumen, and impaired functional receptors for angiotensin II.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] Furthermore, tumor tissues usually lack effective lymphatic drainage.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] All of these factors lead to abnormal molecular and fluid transport dynamics, especially for macromolecular drugs.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] This phenomenon is referred to as the "enhanced permeability and retention (EPR) effect" of macromolecules and lipids in solid tumors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] The EPR effect is further enhanced by many pathophysiological factors involved in enhancement of the extravasation of macromolecules in solid tumor tissues.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] For instance, bradykinin, nitric oxide / peroxynitrite, prostaglandins, vascular permeability factor (also known as vascular endothelial growth factor VEGF), tumor necrosis factor and others.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] One factor that leads to the increased retention is the lack of lymphatics around the tumor region which would filter out such particles under normal conditions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] The EPR effect is usually employed to describe nanoparticle and liposome delivery to cancer tissue.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] One of many examples is the work regarding thermal ablation with gold nanoparticles.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] Halas, West and coworkers have shown a possible complement to radiation and chemotherapy in cancer therapy, wherein once nanoparticles are at the cancer site they can be heated up in response to a skin penetrating near IR laser (Photothermal effect).
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] This therapy has shown to work best in conjunction with chemotherapeutics or other cancer therapies.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/enhanced-permeability-and-retention-effect] Although the EPR effect has been postulated to carry the nanoparticles and spread inside the cancer tissue, only a small percentage (0.7% median) of the total administered nanoparticle dose is usually able to reach a solid tumor.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Functionalities can be added to nanomaterials by interfacing them with biological molecules or structures.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The size of nanomaterials is similar to that of most biological molecules and structures; therefore, nanomaterials can be useful for both in vivo and in vitro biomedical research and applications.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Thus far, the integration of nanomaterials with biology has led to the development of diagnostic devices, contrast agents, analytical tools, physical therapy applications, and drug delivery vehicles.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanomedicine seeks to deliver a valuable set of research tools and clinically useful devices in the near future.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The National Nanotechnology Initiative expects new commercial applications in the pharmaceutical industry that may include advanced drug delivery systems, new therapies, and in vivo imaging.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanomedicine research is receiving funding from the US National Institutes of Health Common Fund program, supporting four nanomedicine development centers.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The goal of funding this newer form of science is to further develop the biological, biochemical, and biophysical mechanisms of living tissues.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] More medical and drug companies today are becoming involved in nanomedical research and medications.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] More companies include Generation Bio, which specializes in genetic medicines and has developed the cell-targeted lipid nanoparticle, and Jazz Pharmaceuticals, which developed Vyxeos, a drug that treats acute myeloid leukemia, and concentrates on cancer and neuroscience.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Cytiva is a company that specializes in producing delivery systems for genomic medicines that are non-viral, including mRNA vaccines and other therapies utilizing nucleic acid and Ratiopharm is known for manufacturing Pazenir, a drug for various cancers.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Finally, Pacira specializes in pain management and is known for producing ZILRETTA for osteoarthritis knee pain, the first treatment without opioids.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanomedicine sales reached $16 billion in 2015, with a minimum of $3.8 billion in nanotechnology R&D being invested every year.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Global funding for emerging nanotechnology increased by 45% per year in recent years, with product sales exceeding $1 trillion in 2013.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] In 2023, the global market was valued at $189.55 billion and is predicted to exceed $500 billion in the next ten years.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] As the nanomedicine industry continues to grow, it is expected to have a significant impact on the economy.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] being investigated for use in nanomedicine.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanotechnology has provided the possibility of delivering drugs to specific cells using nanoparticles.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] This use of drug delivery systems was first proposed by Gregory Gregoriadis in 1974, who outlined liposomes as a drug delivery system for chemotherapy.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The overall drug consumption and side-effects may be lowered significantly by depositing the active pharmaceutical agent in the diseased region only and in no higher dose than needed.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Targeted drug delivery is intended to reduce the side effects of drugs in tandem decreases in consumption and treatment expenses.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Additionally, targeted drug delivery reduces the side effects of crude or naturally occurring drugs by minimizing undesired exposure to healthy cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Drug delivery focuses on maximizing bioavailability both at specific places in the body and over a period of time.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] This can potentially be achieved by molecular targeting by nanoengineered devices.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] A benefit of using nanoscale for medical technologies is that smaller devices are less invasive and can possibly be implanted inside the body, plus biochemical reaction times are much shorter.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] These devices are faster and more sensitive than typical drug delivery.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The efficacy of drug delivery through nanomedicine is largely based upon: a) efficient encapsulation of the drugs, b) successful delivery of drug to the targeted region of the body, and c) successful release of the drug.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Several nano-delivery drugs were on the market by 2019.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Drug delivery systems, lipid- or polymer-based nanoparticles, can be designed to improve the pharmacokinetics and biodistribution of the drug.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] However, the pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics of nanomedicine is highly variable among different patients.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] When designed to avoid the body's defense mechanisms, nanoparticles have beneficial properties that can be used to improve drug delivery.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Complex drug delivery mechanisms are being developed, including the ability to get drugs through cell membranes and into cell cytoplasm.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Triggered response is one way for drug molecules to be used more efficiently.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Drugs are placed in the body and only activate on encountering a particular signal.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] For example, a drug with poor solubility will be replaced by a drug delivery system where both hydrophilic and hydrophobic environments exist, improving the solubility.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Drug delivery systems may also be able to prevent tissue damage through regulated drug release; reduce drug clearance rates; or lower the volume of distribution and reduce the effect on non-target tissue.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] However, the biodistribution of these nanoparticles is still imperfect due to the complex host's reactions to nano- and microsized materials and the difficulty in targeting specific organs in the body.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nevertheless, a lot of work is still ongoing to optimize and better understand the potential and limitations of nanoparticulate systems.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] While advancement of research proves that targeting and distribution can be augmented by nanoparticles, the dangers of nanotoxicity become an important next step in further understanding of their medical uses.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The toxicity of nanoparticles varies, depending on size, shape, and material.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] These factors also affect the build-up and organ damage that may occur.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanoparticles are made to be long-lasting, but this causes them to be trapped within organs, specifically the liver and spleen, as they cannot be broken down or excreted.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] This build-up of non-biodegradable material has been observed to cause organ damage and inflammation in mice.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Delivering magnetic nanoparticles to a tumor using uneven stationary magnetic fields may lead to enhanced tumor growth.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] In order to avoid this, alternating electromagnetic fields should be used.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanoparticles are under research for their potential to decrease antibiotic resistance or for various antimicrobial uses.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanoparticles might also be used to circumvent multidrug resistance (MDR) mechanisms.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Advances in lipid nanotechnology were instrumental in engineering medical nanodevices and novel drug delivery systems, as well as in developing sensing applications.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Another system for microRNA delivery under preliminary research is nanoparticles formed by the self-assembly of two different microRNAs to possibly shrink tumors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] One potential application is based on small electromechanical systems, such as nanoelectromechanical systems being investigated for the active release of drugs and sensors for possible cancer treatment with iron nanoparticles or gold shells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Another system of drug delivery involving nanoparticles is the use of aquasomes, self-assembled nanoparticles with a nanocrystalline center, a coating made of a polyhydroxyl oligomer, covered in the desired drug, which protects it from dehydration and conformational change.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The manufacturing of nanomedicines like lipid nanoparticles (LNPs), mRNA-loaded LNPs, liposomes and magnetic nanocarriers requires precise control of particle size, surface properties and encapsulation efficiency for a safe in vivo use and reproducable efficacy of the therapeutic.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Traditionally, these nanoformulations have been manufactured using batch processes, which can have limitations such as variability in product quality and limited scalability due to the limited mixing efficiency in batch processes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] In contrast, more modern approaches rely on continuous manufacturing techniques to enhance scalability and reproducability.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Microfluidic methods and other rapid mixing methods enable improved control over key process parameters during the nanoparticle formation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] These techniques allow the continuous production of reproducable nanoparticles with narrow size distributions and highly scalable throughput.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The large-scale production of mRNA-LNP Covid-19 vaccines (Comirnaty® and Spikevax®) relies on continuous processes like T-mixing (turbulent mixing).
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] This method enables a efficient encapsulation of mRNA and a high throughput which was critical for mass vaccine production during Covid-19.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] However, scalability rely on parallelization of T-Mixers with multiple parallel operating pumps as the T-mixing is not scalable by increasing the inner dimensions of the T-Mixer.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Characterization of Comirnaty® shows a broad particle size distribution (PDI ≥ 0,2), which is acceptable for vaccines but is suboptimal for small-molecule drugs due to higher regulatory requirements.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] To produce more refined LNPs with narrower size distributions, microfluidic mixers are increasingly employed which can enable more uniform LNPs and a higher scalability due to there inner microfluidic structure as demonstrated in multiple recent studies.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The small size of nanoparticles gives them with properties that can be very useful in oncology, particularly in imaging.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Quantum dots (nanoparticles with quantum confinement properties, such as size-tunable light emission), when used in conjunction with MRI (magnetic resonance imaging), can produce exceptional images of tumor sites.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanoparticles of cadmium selenide (quantum dots) glow when exposed to ultraviolet light.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] When injected, they seep into cancer tumors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The surgeon can see the glowing tumor, and use it as a guide for more accurate tumor removal.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] These nanoparticles are much brighter than organic dyes and only need one light source for activation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] This means that the use of fluorescent quantum dots could produce a higher contrast image and at a lower cost than today's organic dyes used as contrast media.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The downside, however, is that quantum dots are usually made of quite toxic elements, but this concern may be addressed by use of fluorescent dopants, substances added to create fluorescence.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Tracking movement can help determine how well drugs are being distributed or how substances are metabolized.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] It is difficult to track a small group of cells throughout the body, so scientists used to dye the cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] These dyes needed to be excited by light of a certain wavelength in order for them to light up.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] While different color dyes absorb different frequencies of light, there was a need for as many light sources as cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] A way around this problem is with luminescent tags.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] These tags are quantum dots attached to proteins that penetrate cell membranes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The dots can be random in size, can be made of bio-inert material, and they demonstrate the nanoscale property that color is size-dependent.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] As a result, sizes are selected so that the frequency of light used to make a group of quantum dots fluoresce is an even multiple of the frequency required to make another group incandesce.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Then both groups can be lit with a single light source.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] They have also found a way to insert nanoparticles into the affected parts of the body so that those parts of the body will glow showing the tumor growth or shrinkage or also organ trouble.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanotechnology-on-a-chip is one more dimension of lab-on-a-chip technology.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Magnetic nanoparticles, bound to a suitable antibody, are used to label specific molecules, structures or microorganisms.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Silica nanoparticles, in particular, are inert from a photophysical perspective and can accumulate a large number of dye(s) within their shells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Gold nanoparticles tagged with short DNA segments can be used to detect genetic sequences in a sample.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Multicolor optical coding for biological assays has been achieved by embedding different-sized quantum dots into polymeric microbeads.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanopore technology for analysis of nucleic acids converts strings of nucleotides directly into electronic signatures.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Sensor test chips containing thousands of nanowires, able to detect proteins and other biomarkers left behind by cancer cells, could enable the detection and diagnosis of cancer in the early stages from a few drops of a patient's blood.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanotechnology is helping to advance the use of arthroscopes, which are pencil-sized devices that are used in surgeries with lights and cameras so surgeons can do the surgeries with smaller incisions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The smaller the incisions the faster the healing time which is better for the patients.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] It is also helping to find a way to make an arthroscope smaller than a strand of hair.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Research on nanoelectronics-based cancer diagnostics could lead to tests that can be done in pharmacies.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The results promise to be highly accurate and the product promises to be inexpensive.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] They could take a very small amount of blood and detect cancer anywhere in the body in about five minutes, with a sensitivity that is a thousand times better a conventional laboratory test.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] These devices are built with nanowires to detect cancer proteins; each nanowire detector is primed to be sensitive to a different cancer marker.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The biggest advantage of the nanowire detectors is that they could test for anywhere from ten to one hundred similar medical conditions without adding cost to the testing device.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanotechnology has also helped to personalize oncology for the detection, diagnosis, and treatment of cancer.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] It is now able to be tailored to each individual's tumor for better performance.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] They have found ways that they will be able to target a specific part of the body that is being affected by cancer.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] In contrast to dialysis, which works on the principle of the size-related diffusion of solutes and ultrafiltration of fluid across a semi-permeable membrane, the purification using nanoparticles allows specific targeting of substances.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Additionally, larger compounds which are commonly not dialyzable can be removed.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The purification process is based on functionalized iron oxide or carbon coated metal nanoparticles with ferromagnetic or superparamagnetic properties.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Binding agents such as proteins, antibiotics, or synthetic ligands are covalently linked to the particle surface.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] These binding agents are able to interact with target species forming an agglomerate.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Applying an external magnetic field gradient exerts a force on the nanoparticles, allowing them to be separated from the bulk fluid, thus removing contaminants.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] This can neutralize the toxicity of sepsis, but runs the risk of nephrotoxicity and neurotoxicity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The small size (< 100 nm) and large surface area of functionalized nanomagnets offer advantages properties compared to hemoperfusion, which is a clinically used technique for the purification of blood and is based on surface adsorption.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] These advantages include high loading capacity, high selectivity towards the target compound, fast diffusion, low hydrodynamic resistance, and low dosage requirements.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanotechnology may be used as part of tissue engineering to help reproduce, repair, or reshape damaged tissue using suitable nanomaterial-based scaffolds and growth factors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] If successful, tissue engineering may replace conventional treatments like organ transplants or artificial implants.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanoparticles such as graphene, carbon nanotubes, molybdenum disulfide and tungsten disulfide are being used as reinforcing agents to fabricate mechanically strong biodegradable polymeric nanocomposites for bone tissue engineering applications.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The addition of these nanoparticles to the polymer matrix at low concentrations (~0.2 weight %) significantly improves in the compressive and flexural mechanical properties of polymeric nanocomposites.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] These nanocomposites may potentially serve as novel, mechanically strong, lightweight bone implants.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] For example, a flesh welder was demonstrated to fuse two pieces of chicken meat into a single piece using a suspension of gold-coated nanoshells activated by an infrared laser.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] This could be used to weld arteries during surgery.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Another example is nanonephrology, the use of nanomedicine on the kidney.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] The full potential and implications of nanotechnology uses within the tissue engineering are not yet fully understood, despite research spanning the past two decades.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Today, a significant proportion of vaccines against viral diseases are created using nanotechnology.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Solid lipid nanoparticles represent a novel delivery system for some vaccines against SARS-CoV-2 (the virus that causes COVID-19).
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] In recent decades, nanosized adjuvants have been widely used to enhance immune responses to targeted vaccine antigens.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Inorganic nanoparticles of aluminum, silica and clay, as well as organic nanoparticles based on polymers and lipids, are commonly used adjuvants within modern vaccine formulations.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Nanoparticles of natural polymers such as chitosan are commonly used adjuvants in modern vaccine formulations.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Ceria nanoparticles appear very promising for both enhancing vaccine responses and mitigating inflammation, as their adjuvanticity can be adjusted by modifying parameters such as size, crystallinity, surface state, and stoichiometry.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] In addition, virus-like nanoparticles are also being researched.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] These structures allow vaccines to self-assemble without encapsulating viral RNA, making them non-infectious and incapable of replication.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] These virus-like nanoparticles are designed to elicit a strong immune response by using a self-assembled layer of virus capsid proteins.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Global interaction of the various stakeholders is leading to harmonized regulation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] Several therapeutic nanomedicine products have been approved by the FDA and European Medicines Agency.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanomedicine] For market approval, these therapies are evaluated for biocompatibility, immunotoxicity, and a preclinical assessment.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Nanomaterials exhibit different chemical and physical properties or biological effects compared to larger-scale counterparts that can be beneficial for drug delivery systems.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Some important advantages of nanoparticles are their high surface-area-to-volume ratio, chemical and geometric tunability, and their ability to interact with biomolecules to facilitate uptake across the cell membrane.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The large surface area also has a large affinity for drugs and small molecules, like ligands or antibodies, for targeting and controlled release purposes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Nanoparticles refer to a large family of materials both organic and inorganic.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Each material has uniquely tunable properties and thus can be selectively designed for specific applications.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Despite the many advantages of nanoparticles, there are also many challenges, including but not exclusive to: nanotoxicity, biodistribution and accumulation, and the clearance of nanoparticles by human body.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The development of new drug systems is time-consuming; it takes approximately seven years to complete fundamental research and development before advancing to preclinical animal studies.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Nanoparticle drug delivery focuses on maximizing drug efficacy and minimizing cytotoxicity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Fine-tuning nanoparticle properties for effective drug delivery involves addressing the following factors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The surface-area-to-volume ratio of nanoparticles can be altered to allow for more ligand binding to the surface.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Increasing ligand binding efficiency can decrease dosage and minimize nanoparticle toxicity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Minimizing dosage or dosage frequency also lowers the mass of nanoparticle per mass of drug, thus achieving greater efficiency.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Surface functionalization of nanoparticles is another important design aspect and is often accomplished by bioconjugation or passive adsorption of molecules onto the nanoparticle surface.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] By functionalizing nanoparticle surfaces with ligands that enhance drug binding, suppress immune response, or provide targeting/controlled release capabilities, both a greater efficacy and lower toxicity are achieved.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Efficacy is increased as more drug is delivered to the target site, and toxic side effects are lowered by minimizing the total level of drug in the body.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The composition of the nanoparticle can be chosen according to the target environment or desired effect.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] For example, liposome-based nanoparticles can be biologically degraded after delivery, thus minimizing the risk of accumulation and toxicity after the therapeutic cargo has been released.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Metal nanoparticles, such as gold nanoparticles, have optical qualities(also described in nanomaterials) that allow for less invasive imaging techniques.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Furthermore, the photothermal response of nanoparticles to optical stimulation can be directly utilized for tumor therapy.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Current nanoparticle drug delivery systems can be cataloged based on their platform composition into several groups: polymeric nanoparticles, inorganic nanoparticles, viral nanoparticles, lipid-based nanoparticles, and nanoparticle albumin-bound (nab) technology.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Each family has its unique characteristics.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Polymeric nanoparticles are synthetic polymers with a size ranging from 10 to 100 nm.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Common synthetic polymeric nanoparticles include polyacrylamide, polyacrylate, and chitosan.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Drug molecules can be incorporated either during or after polymerization.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Depending on the polymerization chemistry, the drug can be covalently bonded, encapsulated in a hydrophobic core, or conjugated electrostatically.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Common synthetic strategies for polymeric nanoparticles include microfluidic approaches, electrodropping, high pressure homogenization, and emulsion-based interfacial polymerization.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Polymer biodegradability is an important aspect to consider when choosing the appropriate nanoparticle chemistry.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Nanocarriers composed of biodegradable polymers undergo hydrolysis in the body, producing biocompatible small molecules such as lactic acid and glycolic acid.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Polymeric nanoparticles can be created via self assembly or other methods such as particle replication in nonwetting templates (PRINT) which allows customization of composition, size, and shape of the nanoparticle using tiny molds.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Dendrimers are unique hyper-branched synthetic polymers with monodispersed size, well-defined structure, and a highly functionalized terminal surface.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] They are typically composed of synthetic or natural amino acid, nucleic acids, and carbohydrates.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Therapeutics can be loaded with relative ease onto the interior of the dendrimers or the terminal surface of the branches via electrostatic interaction, hydrophobic interactions, hydrogen bonds, chemical linkages, or covalent conjugation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Drug-dendrimer conjugation can elongate the half-life of drugs.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Currently, dendrimer use in biological systems is limited due to dendrimer toxicity and limitations in their synthesis methods.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Dendrimers are also confined within a narrow size range (<15 nm) and current synthesis methods are subject to low yield.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The surface groups will reach the de Gennes dense packing limit at high generation level, which seals the interior from the bulk solution – this can be useful for encapsulation of hydrophobic, poorly soluble drug molecules.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The seal can be tuned by intramolecular interactions between adjacent surface groups, which can be varied by the condition of the solution, such as pH, polarity, and temperature, a property which can be utilized to tailor encapsulation and controlled release properties.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Inorganic nanoparticles have emerged as highly valuable functional building blocks for drug delivery systems due to their well-defined and highly tunable properties such as size, shape, and surface functionalization.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Inorganic nanoparticles have been largely adopted to biological and medical applications ranging from imaging and diagnoses to drug delivery.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Inorganic nanoparticles are usually composed of inert metals such as gold and titanium that form nanospheres, however, iron oxide nanoparticles have also become an option.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Quantum dots (QDs), or inorganic semiconductor nanocrystals, have also emerged as valuable tools in the field of bionanotechnology because of their unique size-dependent optical properties and versatile surface chemistry.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Their diameters (2 - 10 nm) are on the order of the exciton Bohr radius, resulting in quantum confinement effects analogous to the "particle-in-a-box" model.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] As a result, optical and electronic properties of quantum dots vary with their size: nanocrystals of larger sizes will emit lower energy light upon fluorescence excitation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Surface engineering of QDs is crucial for creating nanoparticle–biomolecule hybrids capable of participating in biological processes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The design of inorganic nanocrystal core coupled with biologically compatible organic shell and surface ligands can combine useful properties of both materials, i.e. optical properties of the QDs and biological functions of ligands attached.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] While application of inorganic nanoparticles in bionanotechnology shows encouraging advancements from a materials science perspective, the use of such materials in vivo is limited by issues related with toxicity, biodistribution and bioaccumulation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Recently, however, some studies have shown that certain nanoparticle environmental toxicity effects aren't apparent until nanoparticles undergo transformations to release free metal ions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Under aerobic and anaerobic conditions, it was found that copper, silver, and titanium nanoparticles released low or insignificant levels of metal ions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] This is evidence that copper, silver, and titanium NP are slow to release metal ions, and may therefore appear at low levels in the environment.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Additionally, nanoshell coatings significantly protect against degradation in the cellular environment and also reduce QDs toxicity by reducing metal ion leakage from the core.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Organic nanocrystals consist of pure drugs and surface active agents required for stabilization.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] They are defined as carrier-free submicron colloidal drug delivery systems with a mean particle size in the nanometer range.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The primary importance of the formulation of drugs into nanocrystals is the increase in particle surface area in contact with the dissolution medium, therefore increasing bioavailability.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] A number of drug products formulated in this way are on the market.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] One of the issues faced by drug delivery is the solubility of the drug in the body; around 40% of newly detected chemicals found in drug discovery are poorly soluble in water.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] This low solubility affects the bioavailability of the drug, meaning the rate at which the drug reaches the circulatory system and thus the target site.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Low bioavailability is most commonly seen in oral administration, which is the preferred choice for drug administration due to its convenience, low costs, and good patient practice.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] A measure to improve poor bioavailability is to inject the drugs in a solvent mixture with a solubilizing agent.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] However, results show this solution is ineffective, with the solubilizing agent demonstrating side-effects and/or toxicity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Nanocrystals used for drug delivery can increase saturation solubility and dispersion velocity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Generally, saturation solubility is thought to be a function of temperature, but it is also based on other factors, such as crystalline structure and particle size, in regards to nanocrystals.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The advantage of nanocrystals is that they can improve oral adsorption, bioavailability, action onset and reduces intersubject variability.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Consequently, nanocrystals are now being produced and are on the market for a variety of purposes ranging from antidepressants to appetite stimulants.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Nanocrystals can be produced using two different ways: the top-down method or the bottom-up method.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Bottom-up technologies are also known as nanoprecipitation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] This technique involves dissolving a drug in a suitable solvent and then precipitating it with a non-solvent.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] On the other hand, top-down technologies use force to reduce the size of a particle to nanometers, usually done by milling a drug.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Top-down methods are preferred when working with poorly soluble drugs.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] A disadvantage of using nanocrystals for drug delivery is nanocrystal stability.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Instability problems of nanocrystalline structures derive from thermodynamic processes such as particle aggregation, amorphization, and bulk crystallization.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Particles at the nanoscopic scale feature a relative excess of Gibbs free energy, due to their higher surface area to volume ratio.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] To reduce this excess energy, it is generally favorable for aggregation to occur.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Thus, individual nanocrystals are relatively unstable by themselves and will generally aggregate.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] This is particularly problematic in top-down production of nanocrystals.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Methods such as high-pressure homogenization and bead milling, tend to increase instabilities by increasing surface areas; to compensate, or as a response to high pressure, individual particles may aggregate or turn amorphous in structure.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Such methods can also lead to the reprecipitation of the drug by surpassing the solubility beyond the saturation point (Ostwald ripening).
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] One method to overcome aggregation and retain or increase nanocrystal stability is by use of stabilizer molecules.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] These molecules, which interact with the surface of the nanocrystals and prevent aggregation via ionic repulsion or steric barriers between the individual nanocrystals, include surfactants and are generally useful for stabilizing suspensions of nanocrystals.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Concentrations of surfactants that are too high, however, may inhibit nanocrystal stability and enhance crystal growth or aggregation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] It has been shown that certain surfactants, upon reaching a critical concentration, begin to self-assemble into micelles, which then compete with nanocrystal surfaces for other surfactant molecules.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] With fewer surface molecules interacting with the nanocrystal surface, crystal growth and aggregation is reported to occur at increased amounts.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Use of surfactant at optimal concentrations reportedly allows for higher stability, larger drug capacity as a carrier, and sustained drug release.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] In a study using PEG as a stabilizer was found that nanocrystals treated with PEG enhanced accumulation at tumor sites and had greater blood circulation, than those not treated with PEG.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Amorphization can occur in top-down methods of production.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] With different intramolecular arrangements, amorphization of nanocrystals leads to different thermodynamic and kinetic properties that affect drug delivery and kinetics.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Transition to amorphous structures is reported to occur through production practices such as spray drying, lyophilization, and mechanical mechanisms, such as milling.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] This amorphization has been reportedly observed with or without the presence of stabilizer in a dry milling process.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Using a wet milling process with surfactant, however significantly reduced amorphization, suggesting that solvent, in this case water, and surfactant could inhibit amorphization for some top-down production methods that otherwise reportedly facilitate amorphization.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Liposomes are spherical vesicles composed of synthetic or natural phospholipids that self-assemble in aqueous solution in sizes ranging from tens of nanometers to micrometers.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The resulting vesicle, which has an aqueous core surrounded by a hydrophobic membrane, can be loaded with a wide variety of hydrophobic or hydrophilic molecules for therapeutic purposes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Liposomes are typically synthesized with naturally occurring phospholipids, mainly phosphatidylcholine.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Cholesterol is often included in the formulation to adjust the rigidity of the membrane and to increase stability.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The molecular cargo is loaded through liposome formation in aqueous solution, solvent exchange mechanisms, or pH gradients methods.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Various molecules can also be chemically conjugated to the surface of the liposome to alter recognition properties.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] One typical modification is conjugating polyethyleneglycol (PEG) to the vesicle surface.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The hydrophilic polymer prevents recognition by macrophages and decreases clearance.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The size, surface charge, and bilayer fluidity also alter liposome delivery kinetics.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Liposomes diffuse from the bloodstream into the interstitial space near the target site.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] As the cell membrane itself is composed of phospholipids, liposomes can directly fuse with the membrane and release the cargo into the cytosol, or may enter the cell through phagocytosis or other active transport pathways.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Liposomal delivery has various advantages.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Liposomes increase the solubility, stability, and uptake of drug molecules.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Peptides, polymers, and other molecules can be conjugated to the surface of a liposome for targeted delivery.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Conjugating various ligands can facilitate binding to target cells based on the receptor-ligand interaction.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Altering vesicle size and surface chemistry can also be tuned to increase circulation time.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Various FDA-approved liposomal drugs are in clinical use in the US.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The anthracycline drug doxorubicin is delivered with phospholipid-cholesterol liposomes to treat AIDS-related Kaposi sarcoma and multiple myeloma with high efficacy and low toxicity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Many others are undergoing clinical trials, and liposomal drug delivery remains an active field of research today, with potential applications including nucleic acid therapy, brain targeting, and tumor therapy.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Viruses can be used to deliver genes for genetic engineering or gene therapy.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Commonly used viruses include adenoviruses, retroviruses, and various bacteriophages.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The surface of the viral particle can also be modified with ligands to increase targeting capabilities.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] While viral vectors can be used to great efficacy, one concern is that may cause off-target effects due to its natural tropism.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] This usually requires replacing the proteins causing virus-cell interactions with chimeric proteins.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] In addition to using viruses, drug molecules can also be encapsulated in protein particles derived from the viral capsid, or virus-like particles (VLPs).
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] VLPs are easier to manufacture than viruses, and their structural uniformity allows VLPs to be produced precisely in large amounts.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] VLPs also have easy-to-modify surfaces, allowing the possibility for targeted delivery.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] There are various methods of packaging the molecule into the capsid; most take advantage of the capsid's ability to self-assemble.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] One strategy is to alter the pH gradient outside the capsid to create pores on the capsid surface and trap the desired molecule.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Other methods use aggregators such as leucine zippers or polymer-DNA amphiphiles to induce capsid formation and capture drug molecules.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] It is also possible to chemically conjugate of drugs directly onto the reactive sites on the capsid surface, often involving the formation of amide bonds.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] After being introduced to the organism, VLPs often have broad tissue distribution, rapid clearance, and are generally non-toxic.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] It may, however, like viruses, invoke an immune response, so immune-masking agents may be necessary.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Nanoparticle albumin-bound technology utilizes the protein albumin as a carrier for hydrophobic chemotherapy drugs through noncovalent binding.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Because albumin is already a natural carrier of hydrophobic particles and is able to transcytose molecules bound to itself, albumin composed nanoparticles have become an effective strategy for the treatment of many diseases in clinical research.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] An ideal drug delivery system should have effective targeting and controlled release.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The two main targeting strategies are passive targeting and active targeting.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Passive targeting depends on the fact that tumors have abnormally structured blood vessels that favor accumulation of relatively large macromolecules and nanoparticles.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] This so-called enhanced permeability and retention effect (EPR) allows the drug-carrier be transported specifically to the tumor cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Active targeting is, as the name suggests, much more specific and is achieved by taking advantage of receptor-ligand interactions at the surface of the cell membrane.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Controlled drug release systems can be achieved through several methods.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Rate-programmed drug delivery systems are tuned to the diffusivity of active agents across the membrane.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Another delivery-release mechanism is activation-modulated drug delivery, where the release is triggered by environmental stimuli.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The stimuli can be external, such as the introduction of a chemical activators or activation by light or electromagnetic fields, or biological - such as pH, temperature, and osmotic pressure which can vary widely throughout the body.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] For polymeric nanoparticles, the induction of stimuli-responsiveness has usually relied heavily upon well-known polymers that possess an inherent stimuli-responsiveness.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Certain polymers that can undergo reversible phase transitions due to changes in temperature or pH have aroused interest.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Arguably the most utilized polymer for activation-modulated delivery is the thermo-responsive polymer poly(N-isopropylacrylamide).
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] It is readily soluble in water at room temperature but precipitates reversibly from when the temperature is raised above its lower critical solution temperature (LCST), changing from an extended chain conformation to a collapsed chain.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] This feature presents a way to change the hydrophilicity of a polymer via temperature.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Efforts also focus on dual stimuli-responsive drug delivery systems, which can be harnessed to control the release of the encapsulated drug.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] For example, the triblock copolymer of poly(ethylene glycol)-b-poly(3-aminopropyl-methacrylamide)-b-poly(N-isopropylacrylamide) (PEG-b-PAPMA-b-PNIPAm) can self-assemble to form micelles, possessing a core–shell–corona architecture above the lower critical solution temperature.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Therefore, drug release can be tuned by changing either temperature or pH conditions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Drug delivery strategies of inorganic nanoparticles are dependent on material properties.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The active targeting of inorganic nanoparticle drug carriers is often achieved by surface functionalization with specific ligands of nanoparticles.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] For example, the inorganic multifunctional nanovehicle (5-FU/Fe3O4/αZrP@CHI-FA-R6G) is able to accomplish tumor optical imaging and therapy simultaneously.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] It can be directed to the location of cancer cells with sustained release behavior.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Studies have also been done on gold nanoparticle responses to local near-infrared (NIR) light as a stimuli for drug release.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] In one study, gold nanoparticles functionalized with double-stranded DNA encapsulated with drug molecules, were irradiated with NIR light.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The particles generated heat and denatured the double-stranded DNA, which triggered the release of drugs at the target site.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Studies also suggest that a porous structure is beneficial to attain a sustained or pulsatile release.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Porous inorganic materials demonstrate high mechanical and chemical stability within a range of physiological conditions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The well-defined surface properties, such as high pore volume, narrow pore diameter distribution, and high surface area allow the entrapment of drugs, proteins and other biogenic molecules with predictable and reproducible release patterns.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Some of the same properties that make nanoparticles efficient drug carriers also contribute to their toxicity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] For example, gold nanoparticles are known to interact with proteins through surface adsorption, forming a protein corona, which can be utilized for cargo loading and immune shielding.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] However, this protein-adsorption property can also disrupt normal protein function that is essential for homeostasis, especially when the protein contains exposed sulfur groups.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] The photothermal effect, which can be induced to kill tumor cells, may also create reactive oxygen species that impose oxidative stress on surrounding healthy cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Gold nanoparticles of sizes below 4-5 nm fit in DNA grooves which can interfere with transcription, gene regulation, replication, and other processes that rely on DNA-protein binding.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Lack of biodegradability for some nanoparticle chemistries can lead to accumulation in certain tissues, thus interfering with a wide range of biological processes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/nanoparticle-drug-delivery] Currently, there is no regulatory framework in the United States for testing nanoparticles for their general impact on health and on the environment.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] PEGylation is routinely achieved by the incubation of a reactive derivative of PEG with the target molecule.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] The covalent attachment of PEG to a drug or therapeutic protein can "mask" the agent from the host's immune system (reducing immunogenicity and antigenicity), and increase its hydrodynamic size (size in solution), which prolongs its circulatory time by reducing renal clearance.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] PEGylation can also provide water solubility to hydrophobic drugs and proteins.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Having proven its pharmacological advantages and acceptability, PEGylation technology is the foundation of a growing multibillion-dollar industry.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] PEGylation is the process of attaching the strands of the polymer PEG to molecules, most typically peptides, proteins, and antibody fragments, that can improve the safety and efficiency of many therapeutics.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] It produces alterations in the physiochemical properties including changes in conformation, electrostatic binding, hydrophobicity etc.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] These physical and chemical changes increase systemic retention of the therapeutic agent.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Also, it can influence the binding affinity of the therapeutic moiety to the cell receptors and can alter the absorption and distribution patterns.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] The attachment of an inert and hydrophilic polymer was first reported around 1970 to extend blood life and control immunogenicity of proteins.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Polyethylene glycol was chosen as the polymer.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] In 1981 Davis and Abuchowski founded Enzon, Inc., which brought three PEGylated drugs to market.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Abuchowski later founded and is CEO of Prolong Pharmaceuticals.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] The clinical value of PEGylation is now well established.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] ADAGEN (pegademase bovine) manufactured by Enzon Pharmaceuticals, Inc., US was the first PEGylated protein approved by the U.S.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) in March 1990, to enter the market.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] It is used to treat a form of severe combined immunodeficiency syndrome (ADA-SCID), as an alternative to bone marrow transplantation and enzyme replacement by gene therapy.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Since the introduction of ADAGEN, a large number of PEGylated protein and peptide pharmaceuticals have followed and many others are under clinical trial or under development stages.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Sales of the two most successful products, Pegasys and Neulasta, exceeded $5 billion in 2011.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] All commercially available PEGylated pharmaceuticals contain methoxypoly(ethylene glycol) or mPEG.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] The PEGylated lipid nanoparticle drug delivery (LNP) system of the mRNA vaccine known as mRNA-1273 has been the subject of ongoing patent litigation with Arbutus Biopharma, from whom Moderna had previously licensed LNP technology.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] On 4 September 2020, *Nature Biotechnology* reported that Moderna had lost a key challenge in the ongoing case.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] PEGylation has practical uses in biotechnology for protein delivery, cell transfection, and gene editing in non-human cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] The first step of the PEGylation is the suitable functionalization of the PEG polymer at one or both ends.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] PEGs that are activated at each end with the same reactive moiety are known as "homobifunctional", whereas if the functional groups present are different, then the PEG derivative is referred as "heterobifunctional" or "heterofunctional".
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] The chemically active or activated derivatives of the PEG polymer are prepared to attach the PEG to the desired molecule.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] The overall PEGylation processes used to date for protein conjugation can be broadly classified into two types, namely a solution phase batch process and an on-column fed-batch process.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] The choice of the suitable functional group for the PEG derivative is based on the type of available reactive group on the molecule that will be coupled to the PEG.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] For proteins, typical reactive amino acids include lysine, cysteine, histidine, arginine, aspartic acid, glutamic acid, serine, threonine and tyrosine.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] The N-terminal amino group and the C-terminal carboxylic acid can also be used as a site specific site by conjugation with aldehyde functional polymers.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] The techniques used to form first generation PEG derivatives are generally reacting the PEG polymer with a group that is reactive with hydroxyl groups, typically anhydrides, acid chlorides, chloroformates and carbonates.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] In the second generation PEGylation chemistry more efficient functional groups such as aldehyde, esters, amides etc. are made available for conjugation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] As applications of PEGylation have become more and more advanced and sophisticated, there has been an increase in need for heterobifunctional PEGs for conjugation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] These heterobifunctional PEGs are very useful in linking two entities, where a hydrophilic, flexible and biocompatible spacer is needed.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Preferred end groups for heterobifunctional PEGs are maleimide, vinyl sulfones, pyridyl disulfide, amine, carboxylic acids and NHS esters.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Third-generation pegylation agents, where the polymer has been branched, Y-shaped or comb-shaped are available and show reduced viscosity and lack of organ accumulation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Recently also enzymatic approaches of PEGylation have been developed, thus further expanding the conjugation tools.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] PEG-protein conjugates obtained by enzymatic methods are already in clinical use, for example: Lipegfilgrastim, Rebinyn, Esperoct.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Unpredictability in clearance times for PEGylated compounds may lead to the accumulation of large-molecular-weight compounds in the liver leading to inclusion bodies with no known toxicologic consequences.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Furthermore, alteration in the chain length may lead to unexpected clearance times *in vivo*.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Moreover, the experimental conditions of PEGylation reaction (i.e. pH, temperature, reaction time, overall cost of the process and molar ratio between PEG derivative and peptide) also have an impact on the stability of the final PEGylated products.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] To overcome the above-mentioned limitations different strategies such as changing the size (Mw), the number, the location and the type of linkage of PEG molecule were offered by several researchers.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/pegylation] Conjugation to biodegradable polysaccharides, which is a promising alternative to PEGylation, is another way to solve the biodegradability issue of PEG.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In other words, a quantum dot can be defined as a structure on a semiconductor which is capable of confining electrons in three dimensions, enabling the ability to define discrete energy levels.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The quantum dots are tiny crystals that can behave as individual atoms, and their properties can be manipulated.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Nanoscale materials with semiconductor properties tightly confine either electrons or electron holes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The confinement is similar to a three-dimensional particle in a box model.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The quantum dot absorption and emission features correspond to transitions between discrete quantum mechanically allowed energy levels in the box that are reminiscent of atomic spectra.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] For these reasons, quantum dots are sometimes referred to as **artificial atoms**, emphasizing their bound and discrete electronic states, like naturally occurring atoms or molecules.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] It was shown that the electronic wave functions in quantum dots resemble the ones in real atoms.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots have properties intermediate between bulk semiconductors and discrete atoms or molecules.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Their optoelectronic properties change as a function of both size and shape.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Larger QDs of 5–6 nm diameter emit longer wavelengths, with colors such as orange, or red.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Smaller QDs (2–3 nm) emit shorter wavelengths, yielding colors like blue and green.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The specific emission energy of a QD depends on its dimensions, band gap energy, effective excited electron mass, and effective excited hole mass.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Potential applications of quantum dots include single-electron transistors, solar cells, LEDs, lasers, single-photon sources, second-harmonic generation, quantum computing, cell biology research, microscopy, and medical imaging.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Their small size allows for some QDs to be suspended in solution, which may lead to their use in inkjet printing, and spin coating.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] They have been used in Langmuir–Blodgett thin films.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] These processing techniques result in less expensive and less time-consuming methods of semiconductor fabrication.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots are usually coated with organic capping ligands (typically with long hydrocarbon chains, such as oleic acid) to control growth, prevent aggregation, and to promote dispersion in solution.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] To combat this, a semiconductor layer can be grown surrounding the quantum dot core.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Depending on the bandgaps of the core and shell materials, the fluorescent properties of the nanocrystals can be tuned.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Furthermore, adjusting the thicknesses of each of the layers and overall size of the quantum dots can affect the photoluminescent emission wavelength — the quantum confinement effect tends to blueshift the emission spectra as the quantum dot decreases in size.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] There are 4 major categories of quantum dot heterostructures: type I, inverse type I, type II, and inverse type II.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Type I quantum dots are composed of a semiconductor core encapsulated in a second semiconductor material with a larger bandgap, which can passivate non-radiative recombination sites at the surface of the quantum dots and improve quantum yield.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Inverse type I quantum dots have a semiconductor layer with a smaller bandgap which leads to delocalized charge carriers in the shell.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] For type II and inverse type II dots, either the conduction or valence band of the core is located within the bandgap of the shell, which can lead to spatial separation of charge carriers in the core and shell.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] For all of these core/shell systems, the deposition of the outer layer can lead to potential lattice mismatch, which can limit the ability to grow a thick shell without reducing photoluminescent performance.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] One such reason for the decrease in performance can be attributed to the physical strain being put on the lattice.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Type I heterostructures were found to induce compressive strain and "squeeze" the core, while the type II heterostructures had the effect of stretching the core under tensile strain.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Because the fluorescent properties of quantum dots are dictated by nanocrystal size, induced changes in core dimensions can lead to shifting of emission wavelength, further proving why an intermediate semiconductor layer is necessary to rectify lattice mismatch and improve quantum yield.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] One such core/double-shell system is the CdSe/ZnSe/ZnS nanocrystal.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In a study comparing CdSe/ZnS and CdSe/ZnSe nanocrystals, the former was found to have PL yield 84% of the latter's, due to a lattice mismatch.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] To study the double-shell system, after synthesis of the core CdSe nanocrystals, a layer of ZnSe was coated prior to the ZnS outer shell, leading to an improvement in fluorescent efficiency by 70%.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Furthermore, the two additional layers were found to improve resistance of the nanocrystals against photo-oxidation, which can contribute to degradation of the emission spectra.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] It is also standard for surface passivation techniques to be applied to these core/double-shell systems, as well.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] As mentioned above, oleic acid is one such organic capping ligand that is used to promote colloidal stability and control nanocrystal growth, and can even be used to initiate a second round of ligand exchange and surface functionalization.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] However, because of the detrimental effect organic ligands have on PL efficiency, further studies have been conducted to obtain all-inorganic quantum dots.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] There are several ways to fabricate quantum dots.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Possible methods include colloidal synthesis, self-assembly, and electrical gating.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Colloidal semiconductor nanocrystals are synthesized from solutions, much like traditional chemical processes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The main difference is the product neither precipitates as a bulk solid nor remains dissolved.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Heating the solution at high temperature, the precursors decompose forming monomers which then nucleate and generate nanocrystals.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Temperature is a critical factor in determining optimal conditions for the nanocrystal growth.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] It must be high enough to allow for rearrangement and annealing of atoms during the synthesis process while being low enough to promote crystal growth.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The concentration of monomers is another critical factor that has to be stringently controlled during nanocrystal growth.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The growth process of nanocrystals can occur in two different regimes: "focusing" and "defocusing".
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] At high monomer concentrations, the critical size (the size where nanocrystals neither grow nor shrink) is relatively small, resulting in growth of nearly all particles.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In this regime, smaller particles grow faster than large ones (since larger crystals need more atoms to grow than small crystals) resulting in the size distribution *focusing*, yielding an improbable distribution of nearly monodispersed particles.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The size focusing is optimal when the monomer concentration is kept such that the average nanocrystal size present is always slightly larger than the critical size.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Over time, the monomer concentration diminishes, the critical size becomes larger than the average size present, and the distribution *defocuses*.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] There are colloidal methods to produce many different semiconductors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Typical dots are made of binary compounds such as lead sulfide, lead selenide, cadmium selenide, cadmium sulfide, cadmium telluride, indium arsenide, and indium phosphide.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Dots may also be made from ternary compounds such as cadmium selenide sulfide.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Further, recent advances have been made which allow for synthesis of colloidal perovskite quantum dots.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] These quantum dots can contain as few as 100 to 100,000 atoms within the quantum dot volume, with a diameter of approximately 10 to 50 atom diameters.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] This corresponds to about 2 to 10 nanometers, and at 10 nm in diameter, nearly 3 million quantum dots could be lined up end to end and fit within the width of a human thumb.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Large batches of quantum dots may be synthesized via colloidal synthesis.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Due to this scalability and the convenience of benchtop conditions, colloidal synthetic methods are promising for commercial applications.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Plasma synthesis has evolved to be one of the most popular gas-phase approaches for the production of quantum dots, especially those with covalent bonds.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] For example, silicon and germanium quantum dots have been synthesized by using nonthermal plasma.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The size, shape, surface and composition of quantum dots can all be controlled in nonthermal plasma.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Doping that seems quite challenging for quantum dots has also been realized in plasma synthesis.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots synthesized by plasma are usually in the form of powder, for which surface modification may be carried out.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] This can lead to excellent dispersion of quantum dots in either organic solvents or water (i. e., colloidal quantum dots).
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The electrostatic potential needed to create a quantum dot can be realized with several methods.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] These include external electrodes, doping, strain, or impurities.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Self-assembled quantum dots are typically between 5 and 50 nm in size.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots defined by lithographically patterned gate electrodes, or by etching on two-dimensional electron gases in semiconductor heterostructures can have lateral dimensions between 20 and 100 nm.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The formation of quantum dots can be spontaneous when a semiconductor material is deposited on a substrate and a difference in lattice space exists between them.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] By means of advanced nanofabrication technologies it is possible to manipulate properties of the quantum dots, such as their interactions, shape, size and transparency.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] For example, when negative voltage is applied to a metal gate around a QD, as response, its diameter starts to be gradually squeezed, as a consequence, the number of electrons on the dot starts to decrease one by one, this could be made until there are no more left.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The previous property allows to record the current flow as the number of electrons on the dot, this implies that the energy variates.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Genetically engineered M13 bacteriophage viruses allow preparation of quantum dot biocomposite structures.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] It had previously been shown that genetically engineered viruses can recognize specific semiconductor surfaces through the method of selection by combinatorial phage display.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Additionally, it is known that liquid crystalline structures of wild-type viruses (Fd, M13, and TMV) are adjustable by controlling the solution concentrations, solution ionic strength, and the external magnetic field applied to the solutions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Consequently, the specific recognition properties of the virus can be used to organize inorganic nanocrystals, forming ordered arrays over the length scale defined by liquid crystal formation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] (2000) were able to create self-assembled, highly oriented, self-supporting films from a phage and ZnS precursor solution.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] This system allowed them to vary both the length of bacteriophage and the type of inorganic material through genetic modification and selection.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Highly ordered arrays of quantum dots may also be self-assembled by electrochemical techniques.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] A template is created by causing an ionic reaction at an electrolyte–metal interface which results in the spontaneous assembly of nanostructures, including quantum dots, onto the metal which is then used as a mask for mesa-etching these nanostructures on a chosen substrate.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dot manufacturing relies on a process called *high temperature dual injection* which has been scaled by multiple companies for commercial applications that require large quantities (hundreds of kilograms to tons) of quantum dots.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] This reproducible production method can be applied to a wide range of quantum dot sizes and compositions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The bonding in certain cadmium-free quantum dots, such as III–V-based quantum dots, is more covalent than that in II–VI materials, therefore it is more difficult to separate nanoparticle nucleation and growth via a high temperature dual injection synthesis.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] An alternative method of quantum dot synthesis, the *molecular seeding* process, provides a reproducible route to the production of high-quality quantum dots in large volumes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The process utilises identical molecules of a molecular cluster compound as the nucleation sites for nanoparticle growth, thus avoiding the need for a high temperature injection step.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Particle growth is maintained by the periodic addition of precursors at moderate temperatures until the desired particle size is reached.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The molecular seeding process is not limited to the production of cadmium-free quantum dots; for example, the process can be used to synthesise kilogram batches of high-quality II–VI quantum dots in just a few hours.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Another approach for the mass production of colloidal quantum dots can be seen in the transfer of the well-known hot-injection methodology for the synthesis to a technical continuous flow system.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The batch-to-batch variations arising from the needs during the mentioned methodology can be overcome by utilizing technical components for mixing and growth as well as transport and temperature adjustments.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] For the production of CdSe based semiconductor nanoparticles this method has been investigated and tuned to production amounts of kilograms per month.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Since the use of technical components allows for easy interchange in regards of maximum throughput and size, it can be further enhanced to tens or even hundreds of kilograms.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In 2011 a consortium of U.S. and Dutch companies reported a milestone in high-volume quantum dot manufacturing by applying the traditional high temperature dual injection method to a flow system.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Mass production was due to commence in mid-2015.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] On 24 March 2015, Dow announced a partnership deal with LG Electronics to develop the use of cadmium free quantum dots in displays.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Some quantum dots pose risks to human health and the environment under certain conditions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Notably, the studies on quantum dot toxicity have focused on particles containing cadmium and have yet to be demonstrated in animal models after physiologically relevant dosing.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In vitro studies, based on cell cultures, on quantum dots (QD) toxicity suggest that their toxicity may derive from multiple factors including their physicochemical characteristics (size, shape, composition, surface functional groups, and surface charges) and their environment.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Assessing their potential toxicity is complex as these factors include properties such as QD size, charge, concentration, chemical composition, capping ligands, and also on their oxidative, mechanical, and photolytic stability.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Many studies have focused on the mechanism of QD cytotoxicity using model cell cultures.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] It has been demonstrated that after exposure to ultraviolet radiation or oxidation by air, CdSe QDs release free cadmium ions causing cell death.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Group II–VI QDs also have been reported to induce the formation of reactive oxygen species after exposure to light, which in turn can damage cellular components such as proteins, lipids, and DNA.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Some studies have also demonstrated that addition of a ZnS shell inhibits the process of reactive oxygen species in CdSe QDs.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Another aspect of QD toxicity is that there are, in vivo, size-dependent intracellular pathways that concentrate these particles in cellular organelles that are inaccessible by metal ions, which may result in unique patterns of cytotoxicity compared to their constituent metal ions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The reports of QD localization in the cell nucleus present additional modes of toxicity because they may induce DNA mutation, which in turn will propagate through future generation of cells, causing diseases.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Although concentration of QDs in certain organelles have been reported in in vivo studies using animal models, no alterations in animal behavior, weight, hematological markers, or organ damage has been found through either histological or biochemical analysis.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] These findings have led scientists to believe that intracellular dose is the most important determining factor for QD toxicity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Therefore, factors determining the QD endocytosis that determine the effective intracellular concentration, such as QD size, shape, and surface chemistry determine their toxicity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Excretion of QDs through urine in animal models also have demonstrated via injecting radio-labeled ZnS-capped CdSe QDs where the ligand shell was labeled with 99mTc.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Though multiple other studies have concluded retention of QDs in cellular levels, exocytosis of QDs is still poorly studied in the literature.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] While significant research efforts have broadened the understanding of toxicity of QDs, there are large discrepancies in the literature, and questions still remain to be answered.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Diversity of this class of material as compared to normal chemical substances makes the assessment of their toxicity very challenging.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] As their toxicity may also be dynamic depending on the environmental factors such as pH level, light exposure, and cell type, traditional methods of assessing toxicity of chemicals such as LD50 are not applicable for QDs.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Therefore, researchers are focusing on introducing novel approaches and adapting existing methods to include this unique class of materials.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Furthermore, novel strategies to engineer safer QDs are still under exploration by the scientific community.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] A recent novelty in the field is the discovery of carbon quantum dots, a new generation of optically active nanoparticles potentially capable of replacing semiconductor QDs, but with the advantage of much lower toxicity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots have been gaining interest from the scientific community because of their interesting optical properties, the main being band gap tunability.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] When an electron is excited to the conduction band, it leaves behind a vacancy in the valence band called hole.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] These two opposite charges are bound by Coulombic interactions in what is called an exciton and their spatial separation is defined by the exciton Bohr radius.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In a nanostructure of comparable size to the exciton Bohr radius, the exciton is physically confined within the semiconductor resulting in an increase of the band gap of the material.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] This dependence can be predicted using the Brus model.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] (the figure is a simplified representation showing the excited electron and the hole in an exciton entity and the corresponding energy levels.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] As the confinement energy depends on the quantum dot's size, both absorption onset and fluorescence emission can be tuned by changing the size of the quantum dot during its synthesis.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The larger the dot, the redder (lower-energy) its absorption onset and fluorescence spectrum.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Conversely, smaller dots absorb and emit bluer (higher-energy) light.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Recent articles suggest that the shape of the quantum dot may be a factor in the coloration as well, but as yet not enough information is available .
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Furthermore, it was shown that the lifetime of fluorescence is determined by the size of the quantum dot.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Larger dots have more closely spaced energy levels in which the electron–hole pair can be trapped.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Therefore, electron–hole pairs in larger dots live longer causing larger dots to show a longer lifetime.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] To improve fluorescence quantum yield, quantum dots can be made with *shells* of a larger bandgap semiconductor material around them.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The improvement is suggested to be due to the reduced access of electron and hole to non-radiative surface recombination pathways in some cases, but also due to reduced Auger recombination in others.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots are particularly promising for optical applications due to their high extinction coefficient and ultrafast optical nonlinearities with potential applications for developing all-optical systems.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] They operate like a single-electron transistor and show the Coulomb blockade effect.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots have also been suggested as implementations of qubits for quantum information processing, and as active elements for thermoelectrics.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Tuning the size of quantum dots is attractive for many potential applications.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] For instance, larger quantum dots have a greater spectrum shift toward red compared to smaller dots and exhibit less pronounced quantum properties.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Conversely, the smaller particles allow one to take advantage of more subtle quantum effects.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Being zero-dimensional, quantum dots have a sharper density of states than higher-dimensional structures.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] As a result, they have superior transport and optical properties.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] They have potential uses in diode lasers, amplifiers, and biological sensors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots may be excited within a locally enhanced electromagnetic field produced by gold nanoparticles, which then can be observed from the surface plasmon resonance in the photoluminescent excitation spectrum of (CdSe)ZnS nanocrystals.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] High-quality quantum dots are well suited for optical encoding and multiplexing applications due to their broad excitation profiles and narrow/symmetric emission spectra.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The new generations of quantum dots have far-reaching potential for the study of intracellular processes at the single-molecule level, high-resolution cellular imaging, long-term in vivo observation of cell trafficking, tumor targeting, and diagnostics.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] CdSe nanocrystals are efficient triplet photosensitizers.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Laser excitation of small CdSe nanoparticles enables the extraction of the excited state energy from the quantum dots into bulk solution, thus opening the door to a wide range of potential applications such as photodynamic therapy, photovoltaic devices, molecular electronics, and catalysis.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In modern biological analysis, various kinds of organic dyes are used.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] However, as technology advances, greater flexibility in these dyes is sought.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] It has been estimated that quantum dots are 20 times brighter and 100 times more stable than traditional fluorescent reporters.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] For single-particle tracking, the irregular blinking of quantum dots is a minor drawback.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] However, there have been groups which have developed quantum dots which are essentially nonblinking and demonstrated their utility in single-molecule tracking experiments.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The use of quantum dots for highly sensitive cellular imaging has seen major advances.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The improved photostability of quantum dots, for example, allows the acquisition of many consecutive focal-plane images that can be reconstructed into a high-resolution three-dimensional image.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Another application that takes advantage of the extraordinary photostability of quantum dot probes is the real-time tracking of molecules and cells over extended periods of time.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Antibodies, streptavidin, peptides, DNA, nucleic acid aptamers, or small-molecule ligands can be used to target quantum dots to specific proteins on cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Researchers were able to observe quantum dots in lymph nodes of mice for more than 4 months.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots can have antibacterial properties similar to nanoparticles and can kill bacteria in a dose-dependent manner.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] One mechanism by which quantum dots can kill bacteria is through impairing the functions of antioxidative system in the cells and down regulating the antioxidative genes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In addition, quantum dots can directly damage the cell wall.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots have been shown to be effective against both gram- positive and gram-negative bacteria.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Semiconductor quantum dots have also been employed for in vitro imaging of pre-labeled cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The ability to image single-cell migration in real time is expected to be important to several research areas such as embryogenesis, cancer metastasis, stem cell therapeutics, and lymphocyte immunology.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The use of quantum dots for tumor targeting under in vivo conditions employ two targeting schemes: active targeting and passive targeting.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In the case of active targeting, quantum dots are functionalized with tumor-specific binding sites to selectively bind to tumor cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Passive targeting uses the enhanced permeation and retention of tumor cells for the delivery of quantum dot probes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Fast-growing tumor cells typically have more permeable membranes than healthy cells, allowing the leakage of small nanoparticles into the cell body.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Moreover, tumor cells lack an effective lymphatic drainage system, which leads to subsequent nanoparticle accumulation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dot probes exhibit in vivo toxicity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] For example, CdSe nanocrystals are highly toxic to cultured cells under UV illumination, because the particles dissolve, in a process known as photolysis, to release toxic cadmium ions into the culture medium.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In the absence of UV irradiation, however, quantum dots with a stable polymer coating have been found to be essentially nontoxic.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Hydrogel encapsulation of quantum dots allows for quantum dots to be introduced into a stable aqueous solution, reducing the possibility of cadmium leakage.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Then again, only little is known about the excretion process of quantum dots from living organisms.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In another potential application, quantum dots are being investigated as the inorganic fluorophore for intra-operative detection of tumors using fluorescence spectroscopy.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Delivery of undamaged quantum dots to the cell cytoplasm has been a challenge with existing techniques.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Vector-based methods have resulted in aggregation and endosomal sequestration of quantum dots while electroporation can damage the semi-conducting particles and aggregate delivered dots in the cytosol.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Via cell squeezing, quantum dots can be efficiently delivered without inducing aggregation, trapping material in endosomes, or significant loss of cell viability.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Moreover, it has shown that individual quantum dots delivered by this approach are detectable in the cell cytosol, thus illustrating the potential of this technique for single-molecule tracking studies.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The tunable absorption spectrum and high extinction coefficients of quantum dots make them attractive for light harvesting technologies such as photovoltaics.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots may be able to increase the efficiency and reduce the cost of today's typical silicon photovoltaic cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] According to an experimental report from 2004, quantum dots of lead selenide (PbSe) can produce more than one exciton from one high-energy photon via the process of carrier multiplication or multiple exciton generation (MEG).
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] This compares favorably to today's photovoltaic cells which can only manage one exciton per high-energy photon, with high kinetic energy carriers losing their energy as heat.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Colloidal quantum dot photovoltaics would theoretically be cheaper to manufacture, as they can be made using simple chemical reactions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Aromatic self-assembled monolayers (SAMs) (such as 4-nitrobenzoic acid) can be used to improve the band alignment at electrodes for better efficiencies.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] This technique has provided a record power conversion efficiency (PCE) of 10.7%.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The SAM is positioned between ZnO–PbS colloidal quantum dot (CQD) film junction to modify band alignment via the dipole moment of the constituent SAM molecule, and the band tuning may be modified via the density, dipole and the orientation of the SAM molecule.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Colloidal quantum dots are also used in inorganic–organic hybrid solar cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] These solar cells are attractive because of the potential for low-cost fabrication and relatively high efficiency.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Incorporation of metal oxides, such as ZnO, TiO2, and Nb2O5 nanomaterials into organic photovoltaics have been commercialized using full roll-to-roll processing.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] A 13.2% power conversion efficiency is claimed in Si nanowire/PEDOT:PSS hybrid solar cells.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Another potential use involves capped single-crystal ZnO nanowires with CdSe quantum dots, immersed in mercaptopropionic acid as hole transport medium in order to obtain a QD-sensitized solar cell.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The morphology of the nanowires allowed the electrons to have a direct pathway to the photoanode.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] This form of solar cell exhibits 50–60% internal quantum efficiencies.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Nanowires with quantum dot coatings on silicon nanowires (SiNW) and carbon quantum dots.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The use of SiNWs instead of planar silicon enhances the antiflection properties of Si.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The SiNW exhibits a light-trapping effect due to light trapping in the SiNW.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] This use of SiNWs in conjunction with carbon quantum dots resulted in a solar cell that reached 9.10% PCE.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Graphene quantum dots have also been blended with organic electronic materials to improve efficiency and lower cost in photovoltaic devices and organic light emitting diodes (OLEDs) compared to graphene sheets.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] These graphene quantum dots were functionalized with organic ligands that experience photoluminescence from UV–visible absorption.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Improvements can be seen in the electrical conductivity and charge retention of batteries when QDs are added to anodes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] There exists a constant average difference of around 250 mAh/g in favor of the doped compound for both charge and discharge comparisons, comparing from 0 to 60 cycles, going from 1000 mAh/g to 450 mAh/g in the first 60 cycles for the doped compound, and from 750 mAh/g to 200 mAh/g for the pure MnO.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] A comparison using Graphene Quantum Dots for a NP-SiAl compound not only shows higher discharge capacities but also an improved electrochemical impedance spectroscopy plot, indicating that the battery has better electrical conductivity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] For the case of the NP-SiAl/GQDs, the value of -Z´´/ohm reaches a peak of 300, for 250 Z´/ohm, while for the pure NP-SiAl, the peak of 300 -Z´´/ohm is reached at 650 Z´/ohm.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In terms of energy, each individual quantum dot presents an energy level which is compared to that of an atom.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Extending this property, an artificial lattice (made out of QDs) would have an energy band structure similar to the one of a crystalline semiconductor.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Carbon quantum dots and Graphite quantum dots are the main types of quantum dots used in batteries.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The graphene quantum dots are made out of graphene sheets which are attached among them, forming a morphology similar to a 2D-disk.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The carbon quantum dots have an isotropic spherical structure and are made out of crystalline and amorphous carbon sheets.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] From these common quantum dots, the graphene ones, are usually more crystalline than the carbon ones, this is because they have the crystallinity of a mono-layered and few-layered graphene.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Several methods are proposed for using quantum dots to improve existing light-emitting diode (LED) design, including *quantum dot light-emitting diode* (QD-LED or QLED) displays, and *quantum dot white-light-emitting diode* (QD-WLED) displays.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Because quantum dots naturally produce monochromatic light, they can be more efficient than light sources which must be color filtered.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] QD-LEDs can be fabricated on a silicon substrate, which allows them to be integrated onto standard silicon-based integrated circuits or microelectromechanical systems.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots are valued for displays because they emit light in very specific Gaussian distributions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] This can result in a display with visibly more accurate colors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] A conventional color liquid crystal display (LCD) is usually backlit by fluorescent lamps (CCFLs) or conventional white LEDs that are color filtered to produce red, green, and blue pixels.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dot displays use blue-emitting LEDs rather than white LEDs as the light sources.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The converting part of the emitted light is converted into pure green and red light by the corresponding color quantum dots placed in front of the blue LED or using a quantum dot infused diffuser sheet in the backlight optical stack.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Blank pixels are also used to allow the blue LED light to still generate blue hues.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] This type of white light as the backlight of an LCD panel allows for the best color gamut at lower cost than an RGB LED combination using three LEDs.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Another method by which quantum dot displays can be achieved is the electroluminescent (EL) or electro-emissive method.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] This involves embedding quantum dots in each individual pixel.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] These are then activated and controlled via an electric current application.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Since this is often light emitting itself, the achievable colors may be limited in this method.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Electro-emissive QD-LED TVs exist in laboratories only.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The ability of QDs to precisely convert and tune a spectrum makes them attractive for LCDs.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Previous LCDs can waste energy converting red-green poor, blue-yellow rich white light into a more balanced lighting.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] By using QDs, only the necessary colors for ideal images are contained in the screen.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] The first commercial application of quantum dots was the Sony XBR X900A series of flat panel televisions released in 2013.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In June 2006, QD Vision announced technical success in making a proof-of-concept quantum dot display and show a bright emission in the visible and near infrared region of the spectrum.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] A QD-LED integrated at a scanning microscopy tip was used to demonstrate fluorescence near-field scanning optical microscopy (NSOM) imaging.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dot photodetectors (QDPs) can be fabricated either via solution-processing, or from conventional single-crystalline semiconductors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Conventional single-crystalline semiconductor QDPs are precluded from integration with flexible organic electronics due to the incompatibility of their growth conditions with the process windows required by organic semiconductors.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] On the other hand, solution-processed QDPs can be readily integrated with an almost infinite variety of substrates, and also postprocessed atop other integrated circuits.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Such colloidal QDPs have potential applications in visible- and infrared-light cameras, machine vision, industrial inspection, spectroscopy, and fluorescent biomedical imaging.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots also function as photocatalysts for the light driven chemical conversion of water into hydrogen as a pathway to solar fuel.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] In photocatalysis, electron hole pairs formed in the dot under band gap excitation drive redox reactions in the surrounding liquid.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Generally, the photocatalytic activity of the dots is related to the particle size and its degree of quantum confinement.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] This is because the band gap determines the chemical energy that is stored in the dot in the excited state.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] An obstacle for the use of quantum dots in photocatalysis is the presence of surfactants on the surface of the dots.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] These surfactants (or ligands) interfere with the chemical reactivity of the dots by slowing down mass transfer and electron transfer processes.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Also, quantum dots made of metal chalcogenides are chemically unstable under oxidizing conditions and undergo photo corrosion reactions.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots can also be used to study fundamental effects in materials science.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] By coupling two or more such quantum dots, an **artificial molecule** can be made, exhibiting hybridization even at room temperature.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Precise assembly of quantum dots can form superlattices that act as artificial solid-state materials that exhibit unique optical and electronic properties.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Quantum dots are theoretically described as a point-like, or zero dimensional (0D) entity.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Most of their properties depend on the dimensions, shape, and materials of which QDs are made.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Generally, QDs present different thermodynamic properties from their bulk materials.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] One of these effects is melting-point depression.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p01] Optical properties of spherical metallic QDs are well described by the Mie scattering theory.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] The energy levels of a single particle in a quantum dot can be predicted using the particle in a box model in which the energies of states depend on the length of the box.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] For an exciton inside a quantum dot, there is also the Coulomb interaction between the negatively charged electron and the positively charged hole.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] By comparing the quantum dot's size to the exciton Bohr radius, three regimes can be defined.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] In the 'strong confinement regime', the quantum dot's radius is much smaller than the exciton Bohr radius, respectively the confinement energy dominates over the Coulomb interaction.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] In the 'weak confinement' regime, the quantum dot is larger than the exciton Bohr radius, respectively the confinement energy is smaller than the Coulomb interactions between electron and hole.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] The regime where the exciton Bohr radius and confinement potential are comparable is called the 'intermediate confinement regime'.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] The band gap can become smaller in the strong confinement regime as the energy levels split up.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] This results in the increase in the total emission energy (the sum of the energy levels in the smaller band gaps in the strong confinement regime is larger than the energy levels in the band gaps of the original levels in the weak confinement regime) and the emission at various wavelengths.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] If the size distribution of QDs is not enough peaked, the convolution of multiple emission wavelengths is observed as a continuous spectra.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] The exciton entity can be modeled using the particle in the box.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] with the hydrogen nucleus replaced by the hole of positive charge and negative electron mass.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] Thus by varying the size of the quantum dot, the confinement energy of the exciton can be controlled.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] There is Coulomb attraction between the negatively charged electron and the positively charged hole.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] When the size of the semiconductor crystal is smaller than the exciton Bohr radius, the Coulomb interaction must be modified to fit the situation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] where *μ* is the reduced mass, *a* is the radius of the quantum dot, *m*e is the free electron mass, *m*h is the hole mass, and *ε*r is the size-dependent dielectric constant.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] Although the above equations were derived using simplifying assumptions, they imply that the electronic transitions of the quantum dots will depend on their size.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] These quantum confinement effects are apparent only below the critical size.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] Larger particles do not exhibit this effect.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] This effect of quantum confinement on the quantum dots has been repeatedly verified experimentally and is a key feature of many emerging electronic structures.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] The Coulomb interaction between confined carriers can also be studied by numerical means when results unconstrained by asymptotic approximations are pursued.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] A variety of theoretical frameworks exist to model optical, electronic, and structural properties of quantum dots.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] These may be broadly divided into quantum mechanical, semiclassical, and classical.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] Quantum mechanical models and simulations of quantum dots often involve the interaction of electrons with a pseudopotential or random matrix.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] Semiclassical models of quantum dots frequently incorporate a chemical potential.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] whose energy terms may be obtained as solutions of the Schrödinger equation.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] is the *quantum capacitance* of a quantum dot, where we denoted by *I*(*N*) the ionization potential and by *A*(*N*) the electron affinity of the *N*-particle system.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] Classical models of electrostatic properties of electrons in quantum dots are similar in nature to the Thomson problem of optimally distributing electrons on a unit sphere.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] The classical electrostatic treatment of electrons confined to spherical quantum dots is similar to their treatment in the Thomson, or plum pudding model, of the atom.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] The classical treatment of both two-dimensional and three-dimensional quantum dots exhibit electron shell-filling behavior.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] A "periodic table of classical artificial atoms" has been described for two-dimensional quantum dots.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] As well, several connections have been reported between the three-dimensional Thomson problem and electron shell-filling patterns found in naturally occurring atoms found throughout the periodic table.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] This latter work originated in classical electrostatic modeling of electrons in a spherical quantum dot represented by an ideal dielectric sphere.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] For thousands of years, glassmakers were able to make colored glass by adding different dusts and powdered elements such as silver, gold and cadmium and then used different temperatures to produce shades of glass.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] In the 19th century, scientists started to understand how glass color depended on elements and heating-cooling techniques.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] It was also found that for the same element and preparation, the color depended on the dust particles' size.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] Herbert Fröhlich in the 1930s first explored the idea that material properties can depend on the macroscopic dimensions of a small particle due to quantum size effects.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] The first quantum dots were synthesized in a glass matrix by Alexei A.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] Onushchenko and Alexey Ekimov in 1981 at the Vavilov State Optical Institute and independently in colloidal suspension by Louis E.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] They were first theorized by Alexander Efros in 1982.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] It was quickly identified that the optical changes that appeared for very small particles were due to quantum mechanical effects.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] The term *quantum dot* first appeared in a paper first authored by Mark Reed in 1986.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] According to Brus, the term "quantum dot" was coined by Daniel S.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] Chemla while they were working at Bell Labs.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] Murray and Moungi Bawendi at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology reported on a hot-injection synthesis method for producing reproducible quantum dots with well-defined size and with high optical quality.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] The method opened the door to the development of large-scale technological applications of quantum dots in a wide range of areas.
[src:nanoparticle-drug-delivery/quantum-dot-p02] The Nobel Prize in Chemistry 2023 was awarded to Moungi Bawendi, Louis E.
